1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (For three decades the maximum sustainable input rate in competitive Nintendo Entertainment) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (System Tetris was bounded by the limits of single-finger tapping. The diffusion of two) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (successive techniques, hypertapping and then rolling, lifted that bound and pushed play into) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (level ranges the original game never anticipated. We model input rate as the binding) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (constraint on high-level survival and use tournament data to show how the rolling technique) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (compressed a previously stratified skill hierarchy into a near-flat plateau within eighteen) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm (months.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 546.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (Classic NES Tetris was, for most of its competitive life, a game about endurance under) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (acceleration. As the level counter rises the pieces fall faster, and beyond a certain speed) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (the player can no longer move a piece across the board quickly enough using the gentle) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm (directional presses the game was designed around. The skill ceiling was therefore not a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (matter of strategy but of how fast a thumb could press a button.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm (This paper treats input rate as a measurable physical resource and traces how two) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm (community-invented techniques expanded it. The story is unusual in esports because the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 402.0 Tm (underlying game was frozen in 1989; every gain came from the players, not from patches.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 388.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (The Tapping Regime) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm (The original method, delayed auto-shift play, relied on holding the directional pad and) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm (letting the console repeat the input. This was comfortable but slow, and it capped effective) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm (play around level 29, the so-called kill screen, where pieces fell faster than auto-shift) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm (could move them.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (Hypertapping broke this ceiling by abandoning auto-shift entirely. Players vibrated a finger) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm (against the pad fast enough to register discrete presses, sustaining rates near ten or) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 258.0 Tm (twelve inputs per second. This was physically punishing and unevenly distributed across the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 244.0 Tm (population, and it produced a steep skill hierarchy: a handful of hypertappers towered over) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 230.0 Tm (everyone else.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 216.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (Rolling and the Flattening) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm (Rolling replaced the strained single finger with a different biomechanics entirely. The) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm (player braces the controller and drums four fingers against the back of the pad while the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (thumb steadies the front, so that each finger's tap pushes the pad into a registered press.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm (Sustained rates above twenty inputs per second became routine, and the technique was far) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (less fatiguing and far more learnable than hypertapping.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 100.0 Tm (Learnability is the key word. Where hypertapping was a rare gift, rolling was a teachable) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 86.0 Tm (craft, and its diffusion through tutorial videos collapsed the hierarchy it entered. Our) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 72.0 Tm (tournament dataset shows the variance in peak level among top-32 finishers shrinking sharply) Tj
