/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 690.0 Tm (Modelling the Ceiling) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 676.0 Tm (We formalise survival at high levels as a queueing problem: each piece must be placed before) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 662.0 Tm (the next forces a misdrop, and the service rate is the player's input rate. Below a critical) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 648.0 Tm (input rate, failure is near-certain within a few pieces; above it, survival depends mainly) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 634.0 Tm (on board management. Rolling moved the bulk of the competitive field across that critical) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 620.0 Tm (rate.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 606.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 592.0 Tm (A consequence the model predicts, and the data confirm, is that scoring records became less) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 578.0 Tm (about who could survive and more about who could keep a clean board indefinitely, shifting) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 564.0 Tm (the decisive skill from raw speed back toward spatial planning. The ceiling did not vanish;) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 550.0 Tm (it relocated.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 536.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 518.0 Tm (Conclusion) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 504.0 Tm (The rolling technique is a rare natural experiment in how a single motor innovation can) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 490.0 Tm (reorganise an entire competitive hierarchy without any change to the underlying game. By) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 476.0 Tm (making extreme input rates both achievable and teachable, it flattened a steep elite and) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 462.0 Tm (pushed the locus of skill from the fingers back to the mind.) Tj
